<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,1594,2014]" pageId="10" pageNumber="411">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,282,1594,1619]" pageId="10" pageNumber="411">Taxonomy.</emphasis>
This species was previously known only from the male 
<typeStatus box="[913,1011,1594,1619]" pageId="10" pageNumber="411">holotype</typeStatus>
(
<collectionCode box="[1026,1104,1594,1618]" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/c7yt-hh77" name="Naturhistorisches Museum, Wien" pageId="10" pageNumber="411">NMW</collectionCode>
). We have examined this, and a second specimen from 
<collectingCountry box="[432,535,1629,1654]" name="Australia" pageId="10" pageNumber="411">Australia</collectingCountry>
(see below). The female is unknown. The generic position of this species is not certain. The metasternal-metepisternal impression has a carina anteriorly which extends across both sclerites. This is absent in 
<taxonomicName box="[313,492,1701,1726]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Carchesiopygus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="411" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[313,492,1701,1726]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="411">Carchesiopygus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see above). It is also excluded from 
<taxonomicName box="[990,1169,1701,1726]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Carchesiopygus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="411" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[990,1169,1701,1726]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="411">Carchesiopygus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because the pronotal emarginations are carinate both anteriorly and posteriorly, and the basal margin of the pronotum is wider than the anterior margin, the metacoxae are large and strongly projecting, and the fourth ventrite lacks spines. It is excluded from 
<taxonomicName box="[216,363,1811,1834]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Crossotarsus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="411" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[216,363,1811,1834]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="411">Crossotarsus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because the labial palpi are 
<number box="[703,717,1810,1834]" pageId="10" pageNumber="411" value="3.0">3</number>
- not 
<number box="[783,796,1810,1835]" pageId="10" pageNumber="411" value="2.0">2</number>
-segmented. It does not run satisfactorily to any of the genera in Wood’s (
<number box="[379,437,1846,1870]" pageId="10" pageNumber="411" value="1993.0">1993</number>
) key, nor to the genus 
<emphasis box="[728,896,1845,1870]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="411">Pereioplatypus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Beaver" box="[909,1079,1846,1870]" pageId="10" pageNumber="411" refString="Beaver, R. A. (2007) A new Oriental genus of pinhole borer (Coleoptera: Curculionidae: Scolytinae). Entomologist's Monthly Magazine, 143, 17 - 25." type="journal article" year="2007">
Beaver (
<number box="[1010,1072,1846,1870]" pageId="10" pageNumber="411" value="2007.0">2007</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
. The species is here included temporarily in the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[445,543,1882,1907]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Platypus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="411" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[445,543,1882,1907]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="411">Platypus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as an exception to Wood’s (
<number box="[888,946,1882,1906]" pageId="10" pageNumber="411" value="1993.0">1993</number>
) statement that the anterior margin of the metasternal-metepisternal impression is never carinate in that genus. The other characters of the species would not exclude it from that genus, but it may eventually have to be placed in a new genus, together with a second undescribed, but apparently related, species from 
<collectingCountry box="[708,814,1989,2014]" name="Australia" pageId="10" pageNumber="411">Australia</collectingCountry>
. Further specimens (including females) are needed.
</paragraph>
